A local repository (local repo) in the context of Git is a copy of a Git repository that resides on your local machine.

It contains all the files, history, branches, and configurations related to a particular project.

Setting up a local repository involves initializing a new repository or cloning an existing one from a remote source.
Setting Up a Local Repository
1. Initializing a New Repository:
Navigate to Your Project Directory using git bash

cd

Initialize the Repository

git init

execute "ls -la" command on git bash

If the folder contains the .git folder then intilaization successful

2. Cloning an Existing Repository
Create Repo in Github

Clone the repo we will discuss more later about this
